Ernest Hemingway

Ernest Miller Hemingway was an American journalist, novelist, short-story writer, and sportsman. His economical and understated style—which he termed the iceberg theory—had a strong influence on 20th-century fiction, while his adventurous lifestyle and his public image brought him admiration from later generations. Hemingway produced most of his work between the mid-1920s and the mid-1950s, and he won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1954. He published seven novels, six short-story collections, and two non-fiction works. Three of his novels, four short-story collections, and three non-fiction works were published posthumously. Many of his works are considered classics of American literature.

GamesGeneral_4: Role playing game set in a fictional world of Azeroth where your player develops through quests and "raids".  Each experience brings the possibility of items that enhance your character's look and abilities.  It is very much a social game and a game of teamwork.  The highest rewards are only possible through teamwork in groups of 5,10 and 25.  Your character's point of view is either from the Alliance (good) or the Horde (evil), and there is a robust mythos attached to either. The story line has a correlation to the leader of your faction (Alliance or Horde) and the goal is to eventually rise to kill the bad guy of that particular version of the game.  The game is updated every 2 years or so and a new bad guy and story line are introduced.  My favorite was Illidan and the Burning Crusade. I played so much that my wife actually threatened to leave if I didn't control myself. I miss those days - I felt 100% immersion in the game and in the interaction with my guild-mates

He was the first real bad guy that I encountered playing the game and it took my guild an entire YEAR to grind up to. When we got to him, it took another 2 months to finally beat him.  But we had to conquer other 25-man raids that took months to clear and we had to make sure that all of the raiders were fully geared and stocked and well-read on the game mechanics.  The smallest mistake by any of the 25 players could spell disaster.  We failed quite a bit, but we always laughed and learned from our errors.  It really was a magical time. MoviesGeneral_2: One movie that I saw recently that I really enjoyed was Event Horizon.
MoviesGeneral_4: It takes place in the near future around 2030 I believe, in a time where humanity had mastered space flight and travel. A ship known as the "Event Horizon" had disappeared mysteriously along with its crew during an expedition beyond Pluto. Seven years after this event, the ship had shown up near Pluto's orbit and a team was sent out to investigate and recover the ship along with William Weir who was the original architect of the ship. Upon docking onto the ship the team finds the Event Horizon's crew had all gone missing or were found dead, and it unfolds into the team discovering a portal to hell had been opened up from the Event Horizon's warp drive where they are faced with their worst fears.
MoviesGeneral_16: The character of William Weir was an interesting way of introducing the audience into the universe the movie takes place in. He is originally the main focus of the movie, and we find he is widowed due to his wife committing suicide. He faces trauma from this event, either by nightmares or hallucinations, and when he rediscovers the Event Horizon he ends up going down a path of madness, essentially turning into the villain of the film.
MoviesGeneral_17: It is difficult to say that Weir was good or bad. In the beginning he is considered the main character and he is a relatively good person from what the audience see's. He is dedicated to his work and has a passion for the Event Horizon itself. But his pride and the fact that the Event Horizon gives him hallucinations of his deceased wife as though she were real causes him to start descending into madness giving into what the ship is doing to him and results in Weir killing off members of the rescue team and allowing the remnants of hell to take over him. It would be fair to say he fits both roles but ultimately is more bad.
MoviesGeneral_18: This character is required to set certain events into place in the film, while also showing what happens when the evil that lurks in the Event Horizon takes over someone. There is a lot of themes about facing fears and being forced to relive traumatic events in the movie, and Weir shows what happens when you give into them.

Follow his exploits as he goes on a quest to find enjoyment in heroism again and makes the world slowly learn of his accomplishments.
